      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>There has been some really great learn to play the guitar posts over the last 4 weeks. Here is a selection of some of the better ones.:</div>
<ul style='padding-left:10px;padding-right:10px;margin-top:15px;margin-left:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px'>
<li style='padding-bottom:15px'><b><a href='http://www.learnguitarelectric.com/learn-electric-guitar/learn-electric-guitar-march-28-2009' style='color:#0000FF'>Learn Electric Guitar - March 28, 2009</a></b>
<div><small>Posted on Saturday, March 28th, 2009 in <a href='http://www.learnguitarelectric.com/?cat=4'>learn electric guitar</a> - Comments: (0)</small></div>
<div></div>
</li>
<li style='padding-bottom:15px'><b><a href='http://www.learnguitarelectric.com/learn-electric-guitar/electric-guitar-beginners' style='color:#0000FF'>Electric Guitar For Beginners</a></b>
<div><small>Posted on Thursday, March 26th, 2009 in <a href='http://www.learnguitarelectric.com/?cat=4'>learn electric guitar</a> - Comments: (0)</small></div>
<div>If you do a web search for electric <a href="http://www.learnguitarelectric.com/go/jamorama1.html"  rel='nofollow' >guitar for beginners</a> you will come up with hundreds of pages all offering guitar courses. Most of these will be for home study consisting of Cd&#8217;s and videos or even downloadable versions which can be purchased immediately online.These courses can be quite good and you can progress from absolute basics to a quite high level of playing in a short time. The only drawback with learning electric guitar at home on your own is that you don&#8217;t have anyone beside you to point out any bad playing habits you might be forming. These if left unchecked can become a major problem later on.A good guide is to get a home study course on electric <a href="http://www.learnguitarelectric.com/go/jamorama1.html"  rel='nofollow' >guitar for beginners</a> and then once a month or so take a one on one lesson with a professional just to make sure you stay on the right path.</div>
</li>
<li style='padding-bottom:15px'><b><a href='http://www.learnguitarelectric.com/learn-electric-guitar/play-electric-guitar' style='color:#0000FF'>Play The Electric Guitar</a></b>
<div><small>Posted on Saturday, March 28th, 2009 in <a href='http://www.learnguitarelectric.com/?cat=4'>learn electric guitar</a> - Comments: (0)</small></div>
<div>If you have plenty of time to practice you can learn how to play the electric guitar in no time at all. The rate of advancement for absolute beginners can be quite fast.The very first few days are probably the hardest but also this is when there is more dedication and less chances of giving up. Once you have learned the finger positions for a few basic chords and have learned to strum then the sky is the limit.You&#8217;re up and running so to speak and able to play loads of different songs. It can be quite inspiring.The real difficulty when learning to play the electric guitar comes in advancing from the beginner stage to the intermediate level.</div>
</li>
<li style='padding-bottom:15px'><b><a href='http://www.learnguitarelectric.com/learn-electric-guitar/playing-electric-guitar' style='color:#0000FF'>Playing Electric Guitar</a></b>
<div><small>Posted on Friday, March 27th, 2009 in <a href='http://www.learnguitarelectric.com/?cat=4'>learn electric guitar</a> - Comments: (0)</small></div>
<div><a href="http://www.learnguitarelectric.com/learn-electric-guitar/playing-electric-guitar" >Playing electric guitar</a> can be really rewarding, If you have tolerant friends or maybe even other beginner instrumentalists then you could quite easily form or join a band.<a href="http://www.learnguitarelectric.com/learn-electric-guitar/playing-electric-guitar" >Playing electric guitar</a> in a band is really different from playing on your own and it can also improve your playing by leaps and bounds. photo credit: (nutmeg).</div>
</li>
<li style='padding-bottom:15px'><b><a href='http://www.learnguitarelectric.com/learn-acoustic-guitar/basic-acoustic-guitar' style='color:#0000FF'>Basic Acoustic Guitar</a></b>
<div><small>Posted on Friday, March 27th, 2009 in <a href='http://www.learnguitarelectric.com/?cat=5'>learn acoustic guitar</a> - Comments: (0)</small></div>
<div>To learn basic <a href="http://www.learnguitarelectric.com/go/jamoramaacoustic1.html"  rel='nofollow' >acoustic guitar</a> is not as difficult as it may appear. The difficulty comes when you try to advance from beginners level to higher intermediate levels.With <a href="http://www.learnguitarelectric.com/go/jamoramaacoustic1.html"  rel='nofollow' >acoustic guitar</a>, unlike most other melodic instruments it is relatively easy to play chords. These can be easier to master than picking out melodies on individual strings. You can start with the placement of just three fingers with your left hand (right hand if you are left handed) and simply strum across all of the strings and you have a rich full sounding chord right away.Add a little simple rhythm and you&#8217;re away. Learn a couple of different of chords and learn how to change from one to the other and you will be able to play the accompaniment to many songs.You will soon realise that basic acoustic guitar need not be so difficult.</div>
</li>
</ul>
<div>Which post was your favorite? Let s know below.</div>
